			<li class="" id="comment-92010">

			<div class="user_avatar"><a href="http://newbreedofadvertisers.blogspot.com/" title="Sam Van Eman" rel="nofollow"><img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1c7e17e8a9b603f197f7ee695d33964e?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.doshdosh.com%2Fcomment-avatar.jpg%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /></a></div>				<div class="entry"> 
				<div class="comment_intro">
				<span class="comment_author"><a href='http://newbreedofadvertisers.blogspot.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Sam Van Eman</a> on <a href="#comment-92010" title="" rel="nofollow">November 13th, 2009</a></span><br />
				</div>
				<p>Maki, </p>
<p>Thanks for the links and your willingness to help readers in their work. However, this post rubbed me the wrong way. So many of these points are the stuff of manipulation and monkey tricks. If this is Weinschenk&#8217;s POV, then I have to question how much she actually cares for the consumer. </p>
<p>Marketing succeeds with these pointers, for sure, but at what expense? They don&#8217;t elicit popular respect for the trade nor promote human dignity. </p>
<p>If it&#8217;s true that Producers (marketers and advertisers  in this case) and Consumers are in a relationship &#8211; and I believe we are &#8211; then we must treat each other accordingly. Otherwise, the Producer becomes a mentally strong-arming husband, and the Consumer a co-dependent wife. </p>
<p>Forgive the analogy if it doesn&#8217;t fit well enough here, but in my mind, a manipulation-based relationship is never, ultimately, a healthy one. </p>
<p>Feel free to push back.</p>
				</div>					
