				</div>
				<p>Hey Maki,</p>
<p>The less choices a person has, the better.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s a reason Apple sells so well. By only having a small handful of devices&#8211;and only one for each specific need&#8211;they make it easier for you to buy. What do you need? Portability? Macbook Air. Power? Mac Pro. Power to go? Macbook Pro.</p>
<p>No Macbook TV-345X, or iMac Z-series 4513. Just one model. You either need it or you don&#8217;t. And if you do need it, then you just buy. No comparisons or research to delay your purchase.</p>
<p>3 is better than 13. And if you make sure each of those 3 choices are of the highest, most remarkable quality, then you&#8217;re more likely to have people read and buy your stuff. And of course, utilize the other 10 ways you mentioned, such as focusing on &#8220;you&#8221; rather than &#8220;our stuff has blah blah.&#8221;</p>
<p>Thanks for the great list. I was aware of most of these, but a few were new to me. Either way, an awesome reminder and useful resource for bookmarking.</p>
<p>Best,<br />
Oleg</p>
